<font color="#FF0000">&quot;THAT WHICH WAS LOST.&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct 12 19:55:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art<br>
Well said, what was missing was the welcome home the conquering hero, at the station and in our own home town and in our very own homes. <br>
Before the war the military uniform, the flag was honored and respected. Protestors changed that, it was not the war, but the ugly American at home, the gutless wonderer who slept with the communist/socialistic whore because they were cowards or liberal socialist striving to hold on to their piece of the pie which they saw disappearing with every dollar spent on the war. <br>
Social religious and political leaders in our universities and in some of our churches sacrificed us as lambs, tossed upon the altar of disgrace for the sake of Johnson's Great society. As I've mentioned on another thread, many that sought to stop the war, did so only because they saw that the war was depleting the funds that had been earmarked for their social programs and in the promotion of their own self interest. <br>
We fought a war in Nam with honor and when we returned even our loved ones at home feared to discuss with us what we had done in the war for fear of what they had heard sensationalized over the Six O’clock news. Feared that we were baby-killers, murderers as the demonstrators and protestors claimed we were. We were abandoned by our leaders and our own folks. Instead of an embraced we suffered shame and humiliation to appease the liberal so called social leaders of our nation. So we remained silent and asked nothing in return. <br>
When PTSD symptoms arose among our ranks, it was once again those concepts and labels we faced first and which we had to overcome. Admitting that the war was wrong became a ticket toward healing for some, but in the end we found out that wasn't the answer, it did not bring closure. We found only peace with those who shared our pains and sorrows in the jungles of Vietnam. They were the only ones that understood, they were the only ones that cared. Even soldiers of other wars did not understand us, saw us as having lost the war. That’s why we felt we didn’t belong among the ranks of the VFW and the American Legion. Why, we didn't and don't trust those who say they were among us, but who do not hold onto our views. <br>
We knew we were not wrong, we did our duty, we did not fail, our country failed us, but it was our country and that is what we lost just as the Vietnamese lost his country we lost ours by the communist at our doorstep who won the war at home. A war we were not prepared to fight, nor were we aware of who it was behind those social unrest until it was too late. <br>
Yes, Art your were right, it was &quot;that which was lost.&quot;<br>

